<div id="Story4" style="padding:0 12px;box-sizing:border-box;">
                <div class="section_heading" style="width:100%; background-color: transparent;box-sizing:border-box;padding-bottom:12px;">
                    <div id="web3" style="width:100%;max-width:115px;height:1px;background-color:#D3D3D3;margin:24px auto; ">
                    </div>
                    <h3 style="padding:0;width:100%;font-family:Georgia, 'Times New Roman', Times, serif;font-weight:700;font-size:16px;color:#93888F;line-height:23.1px;text-align: left;margin:0;text-transform:uppercase;">Ecommerce</h3>
                </div>
                <div style="width:100%; background-color: transparent; box-sizing:border-box;">
                    <h3 style="width:100%; font-family:'Helvetica Neue', Helvetica, Arial, sans-serif;font-size:16px;margin:0;padding-bottom:16px;font-weight:700;color:#28121F;line-height:20px;text-transform:capitalize;letter-spacing:-0.32px;text-align:left;box-sizing:border-box;">Uber wants to expand to courier delivery in Kenya</h3>
                    <div style="font-family:'Helvetica Neue', Helvetica, Arial, sans-serif;font-weight: 400;font-size:16px;line-height:25.6px;margin:0;padding-bottom:16px;box-sizing:border-box;">
<figure style="width: 100%;padding-bottom:16px;text-align:left;margin:0">


                        <a href="https://techcabal.com/category/newsletters/tc-daily/">
                             <img decoding="async" 
     	loading="lazy" src="https://c76c7bbc41.mjedge.net/wp-content/uploads/tc/2026/06/Uber-Eats.avif" width="100%" height="auto" style="object-fit: cover"></a>
                         <figcaption style="color:#808080;font-size:12px;font-family:'Helvetica Neue', Helvetica, Arial, sans-serif;line-height:19.8px;padding-top:6px;font-weight:400">Image Source: Uber</figcaption>
                    </figure>
                        
<p style="padding:5px 0;margin:0;">The Kenyan subsidiary of Uber, the ride-hailing giant, <a href="https://www.businessdailyafrica.com/bd/corporate/companies/uber-seeks-courier-licence-in-kenya-logistics-expansion-5489456" style="text-decoration: underline; color: #b61313 !important;">has applied</a> to the Communications Authority of Kenya (CAK) for a National Courier Operator licence, which would allow it to deliver parcels nationwide.&nbsp;</p>
<p style="padding:5px 0;margin:0;">If approved, it could push the ride-hailing giant into Kenya&#8217;s courier market, placing it in direct competition with traditional logistics companies and even the country&#8217;s state-owned postal service.</p>
<p style="padding:5px 0;margin:0;"><strong>Posta&#8217;s long reinvention arc:</strong> In its heyday, Posta was how Kenyans sent letters, documents, and parcels. Then the Internet happened, and emails replaced letters, and like other postal services across the continent, letter volumes fell. According to official data, domestic letter volumes in Posta fell by 5.7% in 2025, and it <a href="https://tech-ish.com/2026/05/15/posta-kenya-is-closing-125-post-offices-heres-why-it-cant-recover/" style="text-decoration: underline; color: #b61313 !important;">shut down</a> 125 of its 625 post offices to save running costs.&nbsp;</p>
<p style="padding:5px 0;margin:0;">Posta did try to <a href="https://techweez.com/2019/04/14/postal-corporation-of-kenya-logistics/" style="text-decoration: underline; color: #b61313 !important;">reinvent itself</a> as a logistics and parcel-delivery company. The problem is that just as it pivots towards e-commerce deliveries, a technology company with more users and drivers wants a piece of the same market.</p>
<p style="padding:5px 0;margin:0;"><strong>Uber is prepared for the market: </strong>Uber already operates its food delivery arm, Uber Eats, across six cities in Kenya, which <a href="https://kenyanwallstreet.com/uber-eats-pushes-kenya-deeper-into-on-demand-living" style="text-decoration: underline; color: #b61313 !important;">generated KES 534 million ($4.1 million)</a> in additional revenue for restaurants in 2023. It also already operates courier services in markets like Nigeria through Uber Connect, allowing users to send packages using the same app they use to order rides.&nbsp;</p>
<p style="padding:5px 0;margin:0;">Uber already has drivers, routing technology, payment systems, and customers, which gives it an advantage, as many courier companies have to build those from scratch.</p>
</div>
